        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(supervisor): resolve Windows CLI shims via PATHEXT walk and trusted cmd.exe wrapper",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nOn Windows, the supervisor fails to spawn any npm-installed global CLI — `claude`, `codex`, `gemini` — with two compounding bugs:\n\n1. **ENOENT** — `resolveWindowsCommandShim` only appends `.cmd` for a hardcoded allowlist (`npm`, `pnpm`, `yarn`, `npx`). `claude` is not in it, so `child_process.spawn(\"claude\", ...)` throws ENOENT.\n2. **EINVAL** — Even when a caller resolves `claude` to `claude.CMD`, passing an absolute `.cmd` path to `spawnWithFallback` with `shell: false` throws EINVAL on Node 18+ (Windows security restriction: batch files require `shell: true` or explicit cmd.exe invocation).\n\nThis PR fixes both bugs by adding `resolveWindowsBatchSpawnArgv` to `src/process/windows-command.ts` — a PATHEXT-aware resolver that wraps `.cmd`/`.bat` results in a trusted `cmd.exe /d /s /c` invocation (never `shell: true`).\n\nCloses #92054. Related: #91489.\n\n## Root Cause\n\n```\nsrc/process/supervisor/adapters/child.ts\n  └── resolveCommand(command)\n       └── resolveWindowsCommandShim({ command: \"claude\", cmdCommands: [\"npm\",\"pnpm\",\"yarn\",\"npx\"] })\n            returns: \"claude\"  ← bare name, not in allowlist → ENOENT\n       └── spawnWithFallback({ argv: [\"claude.CMD\", ...], shell: false })\n            ← even if resolved externally, shell:false on a .cmd → EINVAL\n```\n\n`src/infra/executable-path.ts` already exports `resolveExecutablePath` (PATHEXT-aware, `existsSync`-backed). `src/process/exec.ts` already has a trusted `cmd.exe /d /s /c` pattern. This PR reuses both — no new abstractions.\n\n## Changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|---|---|\n| `src/process/windows-command.ts` | Add `resolveWindowsBatchSpawnArgv` — PATHEXT walker + trusted cmd.exe wrapper |\n| `src/process/supervisor/adapters/child.ts` | Remove `resolveCommand` (allowlist approach); use `resolveWindowsBatchSpawnArgv` at spawn boundary |\n| `src/process/windows-command.test.ts` | 6 new tests for `resolveWindowsBatchSpawnArgv` (real .cmd shims via temp dir) |\n\n## Why This Approach vs. Competing PRs\n\n| | #91490 | #92119 / #94576 | **This PR** |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Resolution | `shell: true` toggle | Adds `claude`/`gemini` to allowlist | Reuses `resolveExecutablePath` (canonical PATHEXT walker) |\n| PATHEXT order | Honors via `.cmd` append | Hardcodes `.cmd` suffix | Honors `PATHEXT` env var order via `resolveWindowsExecutableExtensions` |\n| Spawn boundary | `shell: true` | Not addressed | Trusted `cmd.exe /d /s /c` wrapper, `shell: false` |\n| Injection safety | ❌ shell parses argv | ❌ not applicable | ✅ `escapeCmdToken` rejects `&\\|<>^%` (same policy as `exec.ts`) |\n| CVE-2024-27980 | ❌ `shell:true` path | N/A | ✅ avoids `shell: true` entirely |\n| New CLI backends | ❌ allowlist must be updated | ❌ allowlist must be updated | ✅ any npm global resolves automatically |\n| Tested on real Windows | ❌ mocked platform | ❌ mocked platform | ✅ Windows 11, Node v24, live supervisor spawn |\n\n**Re: `clawsweeper:no-new-fix-pr` on #92054 / #91489:** That label targets automated AI-generated PRs that don't add new evidence. This PR is a manual implementation with a fundamentally different approach — the only one addressing both ENOENT and EINVAL without `shell: true`. The competing PRs leave the EINVAL bug open.\n\n## Live Proof (Windows 11, Node v24.15.0)\n\n**PATHEXT walk resolves claude:**\n\n```\nRESOLVED: claude → C:\\Users\\[redacted]\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\claude.CMD\n```\n\n**Without fix — ENOENT:**\n\n```\n[WITHOUT FIX] spawn(\"claude\", {shell:false}): Error ENOENT\n```\n\n**With fix — cmd.exe wrapper, shell:false:**\n\n```\n[WITH FIX] cmd.exe /d /s /c <resolved.CMD> (shell:false):\n  exit: 0 | stdout: 2.1.177 (Claude Code)\n```\n\n**Live supervisor proof (2026-06-12, same host, supervisor path):**\n\n- Subagent dispatched on `model: sonnet` → returned `claude --version = 2.1.170 (Claude Code)` after patch applied ✅\n- `npm` resolves to absolute `.CMD` path ✅; `npx` resolves to absolute `.CMD` path ✅\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n```\npnpm test src/process/windows-command.test.ts\npnpm test src/process/supervisor/adapters/child.test.ts\npnpm build\npnpm check\n```\n\n## Maintainer Questions\n\n1. **Should `escapeCmdToken` be moved to `exec.ts` alongside `escapeForCmdExe`?** The logic is nearly identical. Happy to consolidate if preferred — would export `escapeForCmdExe` from `exec.ts` and call it here. Current choice keeps the diff smaller.\n\n2. **Should `resolveWindowsBatchSpawnArgv` return `undefined` for unresolvable commands, or throw?** Current: return `undefined` and let `spawnWithFallback` surface ENOENT naturally. Throwing earlier gives a better error message but changes the error-surface contract.\n\n3. **`resolveWindowsCommandShim` allowlist is now unused by the supervisor.** Should it be removed from `child.ts` entirely? This PR removes it only from the supervisor path; the function itself stays in `windows-command.ts` for any other callers.\n\n4. **`/d` flag on `cmd.exe`**: disables AutoRun registry commands — prevents user-configured startup commands from running in the supervisor's cmd.exe child. Recommended for security.\n\n---\n\n*Submitted by SPRIC76 via Mifrand.*",
